  <h1>What is Zero Rated Supply?</h1>
  <div class="byline"><span class="av">SR</span><b>NumberIQ Glossary</b><span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span></div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>A zero-rated supply is an export or supply to an SEZ on which GST is effectively nil and the related input tax credit is refundable.</b></p>
  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>Under Section 16 of the IGST Act, exporters can supply under a LUT without paying IGST and claim a refund of ITC, or pay IGST and claim it back. It is different from an exempt supply, where ITC is not available.</p>
  <div class="callout law"><b>Reference.</b> Section 16, IGST Act 2017.</div>
  <div class="faq"><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is the difference between zero-rated and exempt?</summary><p>Zero-rated supplies allow a refund of input tax credit; exempt supplies do not allow ITC at all.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How do exporters claim the benefit?</summary><p>Either export under LUT without IGST and claim an ITC refund, or pay IGST and claim a refund of the tax.</p></details>
  </div>
  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2><ul><li>Exports and SEZ supplies are zero-rated.</li><li>ITC is refundable, unlike exempt supplies.</li><li>Use LUT or the pay-IGST-and-refund route.</li></ul></div>
